To find $\sin \angle PXS$, we build a right triangle with $\angle PXS$ as one of its acute angles.
We do so by drawing altitude $\overline{SF}$ from $S$ to diagonal $\overline{PR}$ as shown.
We then have $\sin \angle PXS = \sin\angle FXS = \frac{FS}{XS}$.
The Pythagorean Theorem gives us $PR = QS = 10$, so $SX = QS/2 = 5$.
We also have $\triangle FPS \sim \triangle SPR$ by AA Similarity (both are right triangles and $\angle SPR = \angle FPS$), so
